title: Mossberg Persuader 500A 12 gauge w/pistol grip (no butt)
postcontent:
I bought this about 10 years ago and have only used it around 10-15 times.  It's been cleaned consistently but has accumulated some rust as it's been sitting in a closet most of its life.  It's in great condition except for some cosmetic issues (some scratches where the ventilated guard started to loosen up and slide down the barrel...before I tightened it up, the slide caused some scratches which now have some corrosive rust...nothing major and it needs to be cleaned, polished, etc. Last pic is dark but you can see the damage.

Anyhow, the gun works flawlessly.  I did notice once or twice that the recoil of the weapon caused the safety to engage by accident, so the next shot you're trying to pull the trigger and then you realize the safety came on by itself!  I never did take it in to get it tightened (my gunsmith said he'd do it for free but I've been too lazy to go in and get it done), but that would be the only thing it might need.  Most of you could probably adjust that on you're own.

I paid about $250 or so for this weapon and it retails for about $280 now before taxes, etc. but I need some cash, so this is a great deal.  We could meet at one of the local dealers to get the paper work taken care of.  I'd like to have this transaction completed by the end of this month.

title: Browning HP WWII German-officer-owned, tangent sights REPLY TO EMAIL RECEIVED
postcontent:
Note to Armslist users:  First, this gun is no longer available, and I though this posst had been removed long ago.  I will delete it shortly.

I leave it temporarily in order to reply to a rather amusing message received today, which I presume is not typical of those who use this site, or, one would hope, of responsible firearms enthusiasts and owners in general.  It reads as follows:

======
"Message from REDACTED, hit 'reply' to reply to the original sender.
            Dude your grips are pachmeyers.  Vintage my ass."
=======

Of course, there is no way to reply to the fake address used, or I would have been happy to inform Mr. "Mehoff" that 
1) the correct spelling is "Pachmayr" and 
2) my understanding is that "vintage" is defined as more than 20 years old, and I believe the grips are at least that old. Since the original patent on the Pachmayr Signature grip appears to have been issued in 1974, the seller could hardly be claiming they were original to the gun. 
For what it's worth, I'm also not a "dude".

I also include here for your amusement the reply I would like to have written to "Jack", and to all those who seem to feel rudeness is the sine qua non for Internet communication.

============================================================
Dear jackmeoff:

Thank you for your message.  The post in question was supposed to have been removed after only a few days, and it was my understanding that had been done. I will make sure it is  deleted right away.  I will note also I am a computer consultant, and not someone knowledgeable about firearms.  I posted the ad in good faith for a friend who was temporarily both homeless and without Internet access.  

It is my understanding that firearms must be cleaned and oiled, or they can fail to function properly, even causing harm to the user.  Just as firearms require certain care to function, so does society.  However, in the case of human beings, courtesy and etiquette are the oil that enables different personalities to interact with each other without friction.

Likewise, no one fires a weapon without both aiming AND making certain they have identified the correct target.  You may well be an expert on certain firearms. However, if you take the same approach toward your guns and your aim as you seem to toward other people, you are obviously firing a rusty gun at the wrong target, often hitting and potentially harming an innocent bystander - or finding that your shots may backfire.

I would suggest that you consider modifying both your bogus e-mail address and your mode of correspondence to exercise at least the same care and courtesy before you fire an e-mail as you do before you fire a weapon.

Again, I appreciate you calling the ad and the error to my attention, and I will make sure the problem is remedied immediately.

Sincerely,
Karen

==========================================================

TO BE DELETED

In good condition, can be fired as is.  Vintage Browning Hi-Power 9MM owned and used by German officer in WWII.  Heerswaffenamt inspector's mark 140 (W8A140), swastika stamped above, eagle stamped above right, produced at Fabrique Nationale d'Armes de Guerre, Herstal, Belgium. (occupied)  

3 matching serial numbers: 13409a

High-end model with tangent sights (adjustable rear sight), slotted grip for attaching removable wooden shoulder stock (these features discontinued in later models). "MR" stamped in front of left trigger guard. 

Unusual vintage black checkered grips with screws and a single flared groove on each, both grips stamped with European gold lion with letter "P".  We have not found another model available with these grips.

We are looking for a local buyer (here in San Diego), since this item needs to sell FAST, as in today or tomorrow (Thursday 6/18 or Friday 6/19).  Yes, we're all suffering from the economy, and small catastrophes can result in unexpected expenses.  

Asking $3500, but reasonable offers will, of course, be considered, seriously, and with thanks.  Please e-mail REDACTED if you have questions or wish to make an appointment to see the item

title: FEG PA-63 9 mm short
postcontent: The Hungarian Military standard PA-63 version sports a two-tone polished aluminium frame with black slide, grips, trigger and hammer assembly. While unusual for military issue in that a reflective polish was used, it was chosen due to its relative cheapness as well as quicker build time. Problems related to the durability of the aluminium frame were resolved prior to the development of the PA-63 in 1961 with the production of the FÉG R-61 Police Pistol. The addition of .1% titanium to the aluminium alloy solved premature alloy frame wear problems inherent in the earlier FÉG aluminium framed pistols. This development was then applied to all aluminium framed FÉG guns including the PA-63.

title: Chenango County, NY Approves CCW class by Rochester Personal Defense, LLC
postcontent:
After months of quietly accepting Rochester Personal Defense, LLC's DPS101/CCW class, NY, Judge W. Howard Sullivan of The Chenango County Court has made it official that RPD's class will be accepted in his county.

The county joins numerous other counties that Dave and the instructors of RPD have worked closely together with to establish a training and proficiency standard for those that are seeking to carry concealed. All of the training classes include the highly important use of force doctrine, firearm proficiency and safety education, and tons of other information that is (and should be) required for those carrying in public.

RPD's highly successful training class has proven to be reliable and effective for past attendees and has a 100% issuance rating for those that complete the class and submit their request to the judge for their full CCW permit. RPD is the only training in the area that instructs people in the real, actual, laws and use of force of NY State. RPD's instructors include fully certified, experienced, and insured miltitary, law enforcement, and civilian personnel.

Dave and the instructors of Rochester Personal Defense, LLC have made it their mission to provide the highest quality and modern training possible to all students that attend. They believe that if you carry a firearm for any use, you should know how to use it, and more importantly, when not to use it.

Rochester Personal Defense can be reached:
on the web at www.safeinrochester.com
by email to REDACTED
or by phone at REDACTED


Real training for real life


BY AMERICANS

FOR AMERICANS

title: Kel-Tec P-11 parkerized 9mm
postcontent:
Gun is virtually brand new... just barely broken in. Looks incredible. Parkerized finish is awesome.

The P-11 is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the 9 mm Luger cartridge.

The firing mechanism is double action only. The magazine has a 10 or 9 round capacity. The Kel- Tec P-11 is the smallest and lightest 9 mm ever made. Thanks to its locking dynamics and superior ergonometry, perceived recoil and practical accuracy are comparable to much larger guns. The P-11 is especially suited for plainclothes police officers or as a secondary weapon for military personnel. From the very beginning of the design and development, computers have been used exclusively. All machined components are also made on modern high speed computerized equipment. Equally advanced quality control equipment and test procedures ensure a firearm with uncompromising quality in materials and workmanship


TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS
Calibers : 9 x 19 mm Luger
Weight unloaded lbs. : 14 oz. 400g
Loaded magazine : 6 oz. 159g
Length : 5.6" 142mm
Height : 4.3" 109mm
Width : 1" 26mm
Barrel Length : 3.1" 79mm
Sight radius : 4.6" 116mm
Muzzle Energy Max : 400 ft lbs 540J
Capacity : 10 + 1 rounds
Trigger Pull : 9 lbs 40N


CONSTRUCTION

The P-11 has six main component groups: barrel, slide, frame, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine.

The barrel is made of SAE 4140 Ordnance steel heat treated to 47 HRC. The slide is also 4140 steel, and contains the firing pin and the extractor. The rectangular frame is machined from solid 7075-T6 aluminum and houses the firing mechanism.

The trigger connects via a transfer bar to the hammer. The hammer is driven by a novel free floating extension spring. The light weight firing pin transmits the energy of the hammer to ignite the primer. The functioning of the mechanism surpasses all applicable SAAMI safety standards.

The grip is made of the ultra high impact polymer DuPont ST-8018. The grip also forms the magazine well and the trigger guard.

Normally supplied with a 10-round double column all steel magazine, the P-11 will also accept standard S&W large capacity clips. To improve the handling with S&W magazines we recommend using our slip on magazine extension.
